{"title_page": "Internet hosting service", "text_new": "{{ref improve|date=October 2014}}\nAn '''Internet hosting service''' is a service that runs Internet servers, allowing organizations and individuals to serve content to the Internet.  There are various levels of service and various kinds of services offered.\n\nA common kind of hosting is [[web hosting service|web hosting]]. Most hosting providers offer a combination of services; [[e-mail hosting service|e-mail hosting]], for example.  [[DNS hosting service]] is usually bundled with [[domain name registrar|domain name registration]].\n\nGeneric kinds of Internet hosting provide a [[Server (computing)|server]] where the clients can run anything they want (including [[web server]]s and other [[Server (computing)|server]]s) and have Internet connections with good [[Upstream (networking)|upstream]] [[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]].\n\n==Types of hosting service==\n\n{{internet hosting}}\n\n===Fullfeatured hosting process===\n\nFull-featured hosting services include:\n* Complex managed hosting, applies to both physical dedicated servers and virtual servers, with many companies choosing a hybrid (a combination of physical and virtual) hosting solution. There are many similarities between standard and complex managed hosting but the key difference is the level of administrative and engineering support that the customer pays for \u2013 owing to both the increased size and complexity of the infrastructure deployment. The provider steps in to take over most of the management, including security, memory, storage and IT support. The service is primarily proactive in nature. <ref> \u201cInternet Infrastructure Technology\u201d Structure Research, Sept 5, 2012</ref>\n* [[Dedicated hosting service]], also called managed hosting service, where the hosting service provider owns and manages the machine, leasing full control to the client.  Management of the server can include monitoring to ensure the server continues to work effectively, backup services, installation of security patches and various levels of technical support.\n* [[Virtual private server]], in which virtualization technology is employed in order to allow multiple logical servers to run on a single physical server\n* [[Colocation center |Colocation facilities]] provide just the Internet connection, uninterruptible power, and climate control, but let the client do his own [[system administration]]; the most expensive\n* [[Cloud hosting]], which can also be termed time-share or on-demand hosting, in which the user only pays for the system time and space used, and capacity can be quickly scaled up or down as computing requirements change.\n\n===Other===\nLimited or application-specific hosting services include:{{cn|date=October 2014}}\n* [[File hosting service]]\n* [[Web hosting service]]\n* [[E-mail hosting service]]\n* [[DNS hosting service]]\n* [[Game server]]s\n* [[Wiki farm]]s\n\n==Bandwidth cost==\nInternet hosting services include the required Internet connection; they may charge a flat rate per month or charge per bandwidth used \u2014 a common payment plan is to sell a predetermined amount of bandwidth and charge for any 'overage' (Usage above the predetermined limit) the customer may incur on a per GB basis. The overage charge would be agreed upon at the start of the contract.{{cn|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Patent dispute==\nWeb hosting technology has been causing some controversy, as [[Web.com]] claims that it holds patent rights to some common hosting technologies, including the use of a web-based control panel to manage the hosting service, with its 19 patents. Hostopia, a large wholesale hosting provider, purchased a license to use that technology from Web.com for 10% of Hostopia's retail revenues. In addition, Web.com sued [[GoDaddy]] as well for similar patent infringement.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/_mktw/tech/internet/10293025.html |title=Go Daddy Gets Sued |last=Berr |first=Jonathan |date=2006-06-21 |publisher=thestreet.com |accessdate=2010-05-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526080952/http://www.thestreet.com/_mktw/tech/internet/10293025.html |archivedate=2010-05-26 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web| url=https://cebolla.app/| first= Piter | last= Brad| title= offshore hosting | date= 2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Internet service provider]]\n* [[Application service provider]]\n* [[Hosted service provider]]\n* [[Utility computing]]\n* [[Green hosting]]\n* [[Cloud storage]]\n* [[Hybrid server]]\n* [[Infrastructure as a service]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Internet hosting]]\n", "text_old": "{{ref improve|date=October 2014}}\nAn '''Internet hosting service''' is a service that runs Internet servers, allowing organizations and individuals to serve content to the Internet.  There are various levels of service and various kinds of services offered.\n\nA common kind of hosting is [[web hosting service|web hosting]]. Most hosting providers offer a combination of services; [[e-mail hosting service|e-mail hosting]], for example.  [[DNS hosting service]] is usually bundled with [[domain name registrar|domain name registration]].\n\nGeneric kinds of Internet hosting provide a [[Server (computing)|server]] where the clients can run anything they want (including [[web server]]s and other [[Server (computing)|server]]s) and have Internet connections with good [[Upstream (networking)|upstream]] [[Bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]].\n\n==Types of hosting service==\n\n{{internet hosting}}\n\n===Fullfeatured hosting process===\n\nFull-featured hosting services include:\n* Complex managed hosting, applies to both physical dedicated servers and virtual servers, with many companies choosing a hybrid (a combination of physical and virtual) hosting solution. There are many similarities between standard and complex managed hosting but the key difference is the level of administrative and engineering support that the customer pays for \u2013 owing to both the increased size and complexity of the infrastructure deployment. The provider steps in to take over most of the management, including security, memory, storage and IT support. The service is primarily proactive in nature. <ref> \u201cInternet Infrastructure Technology\u201d Structure Research, Sept 5, 2012</ref>\n* [[Dedicated hosting service]], also called managed hosting service, where the hosting service provider owns and manages the machine, leasing full control to the client.  Management of the server can include monitoring to ensure the server continues to work effectively, backup services, installation of security patches and various levels of technical support.\n* [[Virtual private server]], in which virtualization technology is employed in order to allow multiple logical servers to run on a single physical server\n* [[Colocation center |Colocation facilities]] provide just the Internet connection, uninterruptible power, and climate control, but let the client do his own [[system administration]]; the most expensive\n* [[Cloud hosting]], which can also be termed time-share or on-demand hosting, in which the user only pays for the system time and space used, and capacity can be quickly scaled up or down as computing requirements change.\n\n===Other===\nLimited or application-specific hosting services include:{{cn|date=October 2014}}\n* [[File hosting service]]\n* [[Web hosting service]]\n* [[E-mail hosting service]]\n* [[DNS hosting service]]\n* [[Game server]]s\n* [[Wiki farm]]s\n\n==Bandwidth cost==\nInternet hosting services include the required Internet connection; they may charge a flat rate per month or charge per bandwidth used \u2014 a common payment plan is to sell a predetermined amount of bandwidth and charge for any 'overage' (Usage above the predetermined limit) the customer may incur on a per GB basis. The overage charge would be agreed upon at the start of the contract.{{cn|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Patent dispute==\nWeb hosting technology has been causing some controversy, as [[Web.com]] claims that it holds patent rights to some common hosting technologies, including the use of a web-based control panel to manage the hosting service, with its 19 patents. Hostopia, a large wholesale hosting provider, purchased a license to use that technology from Web.com for 10% of Hostopia's retail revenues. In addition, Web.com sued [[GoDaddy]] as well for similar patent infringement.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestreet.com/_mktw/tech/internet/10293025.html |title=Go Daddy Gets Sued |last=Berr |first=Jonathan |date=2006-06-21 |publisher=thestreet.com |accessdate=2010-05-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526080952/http://www.thestreet.com/_mktw/tech/internet/10293025.html |archivedate=2010-05-26 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Internet service provider]]\n* [[Application service provider]]\n* [[Hosted service provider]]\n* [[Utility computing]]\n* [[Green hosting]]\n* [[Cloud storage]]\n* [[Hybrid server]]\n* [[Infrastructure as a service]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Internet hosting]]\n", "name_user": "Piter brad", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePatent dispute)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_hosting_service"}
{"title_page": "Vuoristorata", "text_new": "{{Infobox roller coaster\n| name = Vuoristorata\n| image = Linnanm\u00e4ki Vuoristorata.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = Linnanm\u00e4ki\n| coordinates = {{coord|60|11|19|N|24|56|30|E|display=title,inline}}\n| status = Open\n| opened = {{Start date|1951|7|13|df=y}}\n| cost = 48,000,000 [[Finnish markka|FIM]] (1951);<br/>1,590,000 [[Euro|EUR]] (in 2019 euros, inflation-adjusted)\n| type = Wood\n| type2 = Side friction\n| manufacturer = Svend Jarlstr\u00f6m\n| designer = Valdemar Lebech<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.linnanmaki.fi/en/rides/vuoristorata/ |title=Vuoristorata <nowiki>|</nowiki> Rides |website=Linnanm\u00e4ki |language=en |access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| model = Side friction\n| lift = [[lift hill|Cable lift hill]]\n| height_m = 24\n| drop_m = 48\n| length_m = 960\n| speed_km/h = 60\n| inversions = 0\n| duration = 2:00\n| capacity = 1,320\n| custom_label_1 = Trains\n| custom_value_1 = 4 trains with 4 cars. Riders are arranged 2 across in 3 rows, except for the brakeman's car at the back in 2 rows, for a total of 22 riders per train.\n| restriction_cm = 140\n| rcdb_number = 1073\n}}\n\n'''Vuoristorata''' is a classic [[wooden roller coaster]] located at the [[Linnanm\u00e4ki]] amusement park in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]. It was built in the winter of 1950 and opened on 13 July 1951.<ref name=\"Yle\">{{Cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/jarrumiehiksi_kelpasivat_vain_ilmavoimien_lentajat__linnanmaen_vuoristorata_avattiin_65_vuotta_sitten/9021525 |title=Jarrumiehiksi kelpasivat vain ilmavoimien lent\u00e4j\u00e4t \u2013 Linnanm\u00e4en vuoristorata avattiin 65 vuotta sitten |last=Rita |first=Mikko |date=2016-07-13 |website=Yle Uutiset |language=fi |access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Expected to last up to 15&nbsp;years, it was originally designed as a temporary attraction for the amusement park, opened in 1950. One of the main reasons for its construction was to attract tourists from the [[1952 Summer Olympics]] held in the city. Since then, its temporary status was renewed for extended periods, until it was eventually regarded as a permanent structure.\n\nSince its opening in 1951, Vuoristorata has been the most popular ride at Linnanm\u00e4ki every year. It is the most famous amusement ride in Finland, and a symbol of the Linnanm\u00e4ki park; even the old park logo had a shape representing the climbs and descents of Vuoristorata. Vuoristorata has never had a name differing from the general word used for [[roller coaster]] rides; \"Vuoristorata\" simply means \"roller coaster\" in [[Finnish language|Finnish]] ({{literal translation}} vuoristo = mountain range, rata = track; mountain range track).\n\n[[File:Linnanrollerc.JPG|thumb|left|290px|Vuoristorata as seen from the [[Panoraama]] gyro tower]]\nVuoristorata is also notable for its features. It is actually a copy of another roller coaster, Rutschebanen, opened in 1932 in [[Dyrehavsbakken]], [[Denmark]]. Valdemar Lebech, the Danish builder who designed both of these tracks (and a few others), simply took the original blueprints of Rutschebanen, which had been downscaled due to changes in location, and designed Vuoristorata. Back in the 1950s, Rutschebanen and Vuoristorata were the two tallest roller coasters in Europe; Vuoristorata is slightly taller and longer of the two. Furthermore, Vuoristorata is the last built roller coaster in the world to use [[Side friction roller coaster|side friction]] technology.\n\nVuoristorata is still operated by [[Brakeman#Scenic railways|brakemen]]\u2014as Rutschebanen at Dyrehavsbakken was until the end of the 2009 season, as well as a handful of other roller coasters around Europe and one in Australia.\n\nVuoristorata has been carefully maintained throughout the years. Apart from the oak wooden cars, nothing remains of the original structure. To maintain safety, all the wooden planks have been gradually replaced at least five times. The subsequent restorations have been done while carefully maintaining the original layout; all the wooden parts are replacements but are consistent with the coaster's original design and character.\n\nVuoristorata is among the few roller coasters in the world to have been given the ''[[American Coaster Enthusiasts#ACE Coasters Classics|Classic]]'' status by the [[American Coaster Enthusiasts]] (ACE) club.<ref name=\"Yle\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rcdb.com/1073.htm The Roller Coaster Database's profile]\n\n{{Linnanm\u00e4ki Coasters}}\n{{ACE Coaster Classics}}\n\n[[Category:Roller coasters in Finland]]\n[[Category:Linnanm\u00e4ki]]\n[[Category:Roller coasters introduced in 1951]]\n\n{{Amusement-ride-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox roller coaster\n| name = Vuoristorata\n| image = Linnanm\u00e4ki Vuoristorata.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = Linnanm\u00e4ki\n| coordinates = {{coord|60|11|19|N|24|56|30|E|display=title,inline}}\n| status = Open\n| opened = {{Start date|1951|7|13|df=y}}\n| cost = 48,000,000 [[Finnish markka|FIM]] (1951);<br/>1,590,000 [[Euro|EUR]] (in 2019 euros, inflation-adjusted)\n| type = Wood\n| type2 = Side friction\n| manufacturer = Svend Jarlstr\u00f6m\n| designer = Valdemar Lebech<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.linnanmaki.fi/en/rides/vuoristorata/ |title=Vuoristorata <nowiki>|</nowiki> Rides |website=Linnanm\u00e4ki |language=en |access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| model = Side friction\n| lift = [[lift hill|Cable lift hill]]\n| height_m = 24\n| drop_m = 48\n| length_m = 960\n| speed_km/h = 60\n| inversions = 0\n| duration = 2:00\n| capacity = 1,320\n| custom_label_1 = Trains\n| custom_value_1 = 4 trains with 4 cars. Riders are arranged 2 across in 3 rows, except for the brakeman's car in 2 rows, for a total of 22 riders per train.\n| restriction_cm = 140\n| rcdb_number = 1073\n}}\n\n'''Vuoristorata''' is a classic [[wooden roller coaster]] located at the [[Linnanm\u00e4ki]] amusement park in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]. It was built in the winter of 1950 and opened on 13 July 1951.<ref name=\"Yle\">{{Cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/jarrumiehiksi_kelpasivat_vain_ilmavoimien_lentajat__linnanmaen_vuoristorata_avattiin_65_vuotta_sitten/9021525 |title=Jarrumiehiksi kelpasivat vain ilmavoimien lent\u00e4j\u00e4t \u2013 Linnanm\u00e4en vuoristorata avattiin 65 vuotta sitten |last=Rita |first=Mikko |date=2016-07-13 |website=Yle Uutiset |language=fi |access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Expected to last up to 15&nbsp;years, it was originally designed as a temporary attraction for the amusement park, opened in 1950. One of the main reasons for its construction was to attract tourists from the [[1952 Summer Olympics]] held in the city. Since then, its temporary status was renewed for extended periods, until it was eventually regarded as a permanent structure.\n\nSince its opening in 1951, Vuoristorata has been the most popular ride at Linnanm\u00e4ki every year. It is the most famous amusement ride in Finland, and a symbol of the Linnanm\u00e4ki park; even the old park logo had a shape representing the climbs and descents of Vuoristorata. Vuoristorata has never had a name differing from the general word used for [[roller coaster]] rides; \"Vuoristorata\" simply means \"roller coaster\" in [[Finnish language|Finnish]] ({{literal translation}} vuoristo = mountain range, rata = track; mountain range track).\n\n[[File:Linnanrollerc.JPG|thumb|left|290px|Vuoristorata as seen from the [[Panoraama]] gyro tower]]\nVuoristorata is also notable for its features. It is actually a copy of another roller coaster, Rutschebanen, opened in 1932 in [[Dyrehavsbakken]], [[Denmark]]. Valdemar Lebech, the Danish builder who designed both of these tracks (and a few others), simply took the original blueprints of Rutschebanen, which had been downscaled due to changes in location, and designed Vuoristorata. Back in the 1950s, Rutschebanen and Vuoristorata were the two tallest roller coasters in Europe; Vuoristorata is slightly taller and longer of the two. Furthermore, Vuoristorata is the last built roller coaster in the world to use [[Side friction roller coaster|side friction]] technology.\n\nVuoristorata is still operated by [[Brakeman#Scenic railways|brakemen]]\u2014as Rutschebanen at Dyrehavsbakken was until the end of the 2009 season, as well as a handful of other roller coasters around Europe and one in Australia.\n\nVuoristorata has been carefully maintained throughout the years. Apart from the oak wooden cars, nothing remains of the original structure. To maintain safety, all the wooden planks have been gradually replaced at least five times. The subsequent restorations have been done while carefully maintaining the original layout; all the wooden parts are replacements but are consistent with the coaster's original design and character.\n\nVuoristorata is among the few roller coasters in the world to have been given the ''[[American Coaster Enthusiasts#ACE Coasters Classics|Classic]]'' status by the [[American Coaster Enthusiasts]] (ACE) club.<ref name=\"Yle\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rcdb.com/1073.htm The Roller Coaster Database's profile]\n\n{{Linnanm\u00e4ki Coasters}}\n{{ACE Coaster Classics}}\n\n[[Category:Roller coasters in Finland]]\n[[Category:Linnanm\u00e4ki]]\n[[Category:Roller coasters introduced in 1951]]\n\n{{Amusement-ride-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zarex", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vuoristorata"}
